    <entry>
        <title>How to experience 86-DOS?</title>
        <author>
            <name>Legacy Installer</name>
        </author>
        <link href="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-86-dos/"/>
        <id>https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/how-to-experience-86-dos/</id>
            <category term="Other Emulator"/>
            <category term="DOS"/>

        <updated>2022-03-24T19:09:48+05:30</updated>
            <summary>
                <![CDATA[
                        <img src="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/86DOS-2-2.png" alt="86DOS asking for date" />
                    86-DOS is a "quick and dirty" operating system clone of CP/M created by Seattle Computer Products for their 8086 S-100&hellip;
                ]]>
            </summary>
        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                    <img src="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/86DOS-2-2.png" alt="86DOS asking for date" />
                <p>86-DOS is a "quick and dirty" operating system clone of CP/M created by Seattle Computer Products for their 8086 S-100 systems. It was later bought by Microsoft and used as the basis for IBM PC-DOS and MS-DOS. Sadly, it cannot be emulated by any software we have installed so far. Thankfully, there exist an emulator, which is very tiny in size and we can run 86-DOS on it.</p>
<p>You can Download them here:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/files/86DOSonlinux.tar.xz">86DOS Linux version</a></li>
<li><a href="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/files/86DOSonwindows.zip">86DOS Windows version</a></li>
</ul>
<h1>Using 86-DOS</h1>
<p>It is very easy to start using 86-DOS. On Linux, extract the above archive and right click on the 86dos.sh file and choose "Run as a Program" or run the shell file the way you run any other shell file. On Windows, extract the above archive and double click the Runme.bat file. The Virtual Machine will start.</p>
<figure class="post__image post__image--center"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/86DOS-1.png" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw" srcset="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-1-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-1-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-1-md.png 768w"  alt="86DOS emulator screenshot" width="834" height="630"></figure>Press Enter (↩) until a prompt appears and then type a capital "B" without quotes and press Enter (↩) to start 86DOS.</p>
<figure class="post__image post__image--center"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/86DOS-2.png" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw" srcset="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-2-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-2-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-2-md.png 768w"  alt="86DOS emulator with 86DOS started screenshot" width="834" height="630"></figure>Enter a date from 1980s to continue. You should not enter dates after year 2000 due to a bug in almost all software released before that year. For example, enter 03-23-82 and press Enter(↩). 86-DOS will start. You can enter the DIR command to see a list of available files.</p>
<figure class="post__image post__image--center"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/86DOS-3.png" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 100vw" srcset="https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-3-xs.png 300w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-3-sm.png 480w ,https://virtualhub.legacyinstaller.pcriot.com/media/posts/2/responsive/86DOS-3-md.png 768w"  alt="DIR command running in 86DOS" width="834" height="630"></figure>That's it! We used 86-DOS, an operating system launched in 1981 after 41 years (at the time of writing this tutorial).</p>
<h1>Manuals</h1>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20200110094102/http://www.patersontech.com/dos/docs/86_Dos_inst.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">86-DOS Instruction Manual</a></li>
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210216072829/http://bitsavers.org/pdf/seattleComputer/86-DOS_0.3_Programmers_Manual_1980.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">86-DOS Programmer's Manual</a></li>
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210216073337/http://bitsavers.org/pdf/seattleComputer/86-DOS_0.3_Users_Manual_1980.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">86-DOS User's Manual</a></li>
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210216073838/http://bitsavers.org/pdf/seattleComputer/86-DOS_1.0_Addendum.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">86-DOS 1.0 Addendum</a></li>
</ul>
<h1>Related Pages</h1>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://winworldpc.com/product/86-dos/100" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WinWorld Page</a></li>
<li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/86-DOS" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Wikipedia</a></li>
<li><a href="https://betawiki.net/wiki/86-DOS" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BetaWiki</a></li>
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20200102191543/http://www.patersontech.com/dos/origins-of-dos.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tim Paterson's Site (Wayback Machine)</a></li>
<li><a href="https://dosmandrivel.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Tim Paterson's Blog</a></li>
</ul>
<h1>Credits</h1>
<p>The emulator which is linked above was created by <a href="mailto:peter.schorn@acm.org" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Peter Schorn</a>. You can visit <a href="https://schorn.ch/altair.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">his website</a> to download the original emulator and lots of other software.</p>
            ]]>
        </content>
